&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt; &amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt; &amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;Based on the concept of SDD, I decided to use spec-kit to test the performance of weaker models. The test task was: to add a publish button to hugo-admin.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;Unfortunately, the performance is still not quite up to par. What&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;s rather amusing is the content it output in the middle:
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;Then it skipped the tests. I can only say that ChatGLM 4.6 is an AI model that doesn&lt;span class="s1"&gt;&amp;#39;t get bogged down in internal struggles. Here is the [commit](https://github.com/Svtter/hugo-admin/commit/ad7891e0038f154f37a4b65325746dce1c00d1b4) it submitted.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;Afterwards, I switched to `doubao-seed-code` to continue testing other features, but the performance of doubao-seed-code combined with Claude Code wasn&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;t great either. You can check out its &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;commit&lt;span class="o"&gt;](&lt;/span&gt;https://github.com/Svtter/hugo-admin/commit/9acd83940da558c1335f036e2dc475062166869d&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;In the end, I completed the entire functionality using Trae &lt;span class="o"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;which does not support spec-kit&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;. The corresponding &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;commit&lt;span class="o"&gt;](&lt;/span&gt;https://github.com/Svtter/hugo-admin/commit/53f895017e9d2b94880f5385562993274076d7a7&lt;span class="o"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="c1"&gt;## Summary&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;- If you can manually manage the current context and some obvious &lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;information the model tends to forget,&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;then&lt;/span&gt; you can completely avoid using &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;spec-kit&lt;span class="o"&gt;][&lt;/span&gt;1&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; when working with Claude Code. This thing is a token hog—it essentially uses a sledgehammer to crack a nut.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;- &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;spec-kit&lt;span class="o"&gt;][&lt;/span&gt;1&lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; does not support Trae, and Trae doesn&lt;span class="err"&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;t need that support to perform well.
